<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>On startup, <code>xrandr</code> yields the following output:<br/> <code>Screen 0: minimum 8 x 8, current 1920 x 1080, maximum 32767 x 32767</code><br/> <code>DP-0 disconnected primary (normal left inverted right x axis y axis)</code><br/> <code>DP-1 disconnected (normal left inverted right x axis y axis)</code><br/> <code>eDP-1-0 connected 1920x1080+0+0 (normal left inverted right x axis y axis) 309mm x 174mm</code><br/> <code>1920x1080 120.00*+ 96.03 72.02 60.00 50.01 48.00 60.00</code><br/> <code>1680x1050 120.00</code><br/> <code>1280x1024 120.00</code><br/> <code>1440x900 120.00</code><br/> <code>1280x800 120.00</code><br/> <code>1280x720 120.00</code><br/> <code>1024x768 120.00</code><br/> <code>800x600 120.00</code><br/> <code>640x480 120.00</code><br/> <code>HDMI-A-1-0 disconnected (normal left inverted right x axis y axis)</code> </p> <p>However, the screen in not running at 120Hz as xrandr thinks, it runs something around 60Hz. It is very evident if you move the cursor around (it&#39;s less smooth, you can see individual frames). If I run <code>xrandr --output eDP-1-0 --mode 1920x1080 --rate 120</code>, nothing changes, however if I first set it to 60Hz using similar command and <em>then</em> back to 120, the display actually switches to 120, the cursor starts to move as intended. </p> <p>I guess I can write a simple script that would do this on startup, but it is a band-aid fix. Any ideas why xrandr thinks of wrong refresh rate? I tried googling the issue and only found basic xrandr guides. Thanks in advance!</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/TheDenast"> /u/TheDenast </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/wgfgkm/xrandr_does_not_show_correct_refresh_rate_on/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/archlinux/comments/wgfgkm/xrandr_does_not_show_correct_refresh_rate_on/">[comments]</a></span>